<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1059,961,1041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">
D i a g n o s i s: The combination of red marking on the portal disc, elytral apex yellow, and enlarged 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[397,410,986,1000]" fontSize="6" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">th</superScript>
antennomere (
<figureCitation box="[571,649,990,1012]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) will distinguish the members of this species from congeners. The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[513,637,1019,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[513,637,1019,1040]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">Pujoliclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2014 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[898,1033,1019,1041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018" pagination="727 - 756" refId="ref53564" refString="OPITZ W. (2014 d): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the checkered beetle genus Pujoliclerus PIC (Coleoptera: Cleridae: Peloniinae). - The Coleopteristss Bulletin 68 (4): 727 - 756." type="journal article" year="2014">OPITZ 2014d</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1059,1056,1401]" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 
<quantity box="[516,597,1056,1078]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018" unit="mm" value="4.5">4.5 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,1057,1078]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,1056,1079]" captionStart="Figs 350-353" captionStartId="115.[151,191,1511,1533]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,200,1497]" captionTargetId="figure@115.[153,1061,200,1498]" captionTargetPageId="115" captionText="Figs 350-353: Habitus; (350) Pujoliclerus tuxtlas; (351) P. variolus; (352) Sicamus suprus; (353) Sirpa acara." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746838" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746838/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">Fig. 350</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium mostly testaceous, upper frons and epicranium black at middle; antenna black; prothorax tricolorous, venter yellow, pronotum yellow at sides, with red marking adjacent to black marking at middle; pterothorax dark brown; elytra dark brown except apex yellow; legs bicolorous, mostly testaceous, become less infuscated from prothoracic legs to metathoracic legs; abdomen brown. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[159,233,1233,1255]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
) capitate, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[354,367,1229,1243]" fontSize="6" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">th</superScript>
antennomere expanded, capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovate; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye wider than frons (EW/FW 25/20). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[441,531,1291,1313]" captionStart="Figs 194-200" captionStartId="82.[151,191,1513,1535]" captionTargetBox="[163,1057,222,1486]" captionTargetId="figure@82.[152,1057,206,1504]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="Figs 194-200: Pronota; (194) Perilypus izabal; (195) P. apunctus; (196) Neorthopleura thomasi; (197) Ampleris itaituba; (198) Cregya fuscomacula; (199) Ichnea paraguayensis; (200) Pujoliclerus tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746770" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746770/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">Fig. 200</figureCitation>
) quadrate (PW/PL 67/67), disc coarsely punctate, lateral tubercle well developed; elytral asetiferous punctures arranged into 10 striae, punctures extend to elytral apex (EL/EW 205/48). Abdomen: Pygidium quadrate 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1051,1058,1350,1372]" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">/</emphasis>
scutiform, posterior margin broadly concave; aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[768,860,1379,1401]" captionStart="Figs 255-261" captionStartId="92.[151,191,1238,1260]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,200,1225]" captionTargetId="figure@92.[153,1061,200,1225]" captionTargetPageId="92" captionText="Figs 255-261: Aedeagi; (255) Pujoliclerus tuxtlas; (256) Sicamus suprus; (257) Sirpa acara; (258) Sirpa latiflava; (259) Topainca pachacutii; (260) Pelonium atrigonatium; (261) Ordinis taxis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746790" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746790/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="1018">Fig. 255.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
